4.=>What is a Database?

Correct Answer:

A database is a collection of tables used to store data in the form of rows and columns.

Tamil:

Database-na rows & columns-oda structure-la data store panna use aagura collection of tables.

One English sentence to tell outside:

â€œDatabase = Collection of Tablesâ€

âœ”ï¸ Structure Hierarchy (Very Important)


MySQL Server
    â†“
Database (Collection of tables)
    â†“
Tables (Collection of rows)
    â†“
Rows (Collection of column values)
    â†“
Columns (Fields â€“ structure)


âœ”ï¸ Who Controls What?


| Element           | Structure control | Data control |
| ----------------- | ----------------- | ------------ |
| **Database**      | DDL âœ”ï¸            | DML âœ–ï¸       |
| **Table**         | DDL âœ”ï¸            | DML âœ–ï¸       |
| **Column**        | DDL âœ”ï¸            | DML âœ–ï¸       |
| **Row (Records)** | DDL âœ–ï¸            | DML âœ”ï¸       |


ğŸ”¥ Key Line (Remember this!)

DDL commands handle structure (Database, Table, Column)
DML commands handle data (Rows


âŒ Your Sentences â€“ Mistakes Fixed


| Mistake                                                       | Correct                                              |
| ------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| â€œcollection of database la senthathuthan oru GUIâ€             | GUI is not a collection. Workbench = GUI client only |
| â€œRow va handle panna mudiyathu with DDLâ€                      | âœ” correct: Rows are handled only by DML              |
| â€œcollection of database vachi control panna mudiyum with DDLâ€ | âœ” yes: create, drop, rename database                 |



âœ”ï¸ Correct Summary (Easy to memorize)

Database = Collection of Tables

Table = Collection of Rows

Row = Collection of Column Values

Column = Field name + datatype

DDL â†’ Structure only

DML â†’ Data only



Example commands


-- DDL
CREATE DATABASE school;
CREATE TABLE student(id INT, name VARCHAR(20));

-- DML
INSERT INTO student VALUES(1,'Gowtham');







