6.=>âœ”ï¸ MySQL Important Data Types

1ï¸.Number Types

| Data type    | Use                                | Example      |
| ------------ | ---------------------------------- | ------------ |
| INT          | Whole numbers                      | 10, 200, -50 |
| BIGINT       | Very large numbers                 | Phone number |
| FLOAT        | Small decimal values (approximate) | 12.56        |
| DOUBLE       | More accurate decimals             | 78.987654    |
| DECIMAL(x,y) | Money values (exact)               | 999.99       |


2ï¸.Text (String) Types


| Type       | Use                  | Example                   |
| ---------- | -------------------- | ------------------------- |
| VARCHAR(n) | Variable-length text | name VARCHAR(50)          |
| CHAR(n)    | Fixed length text    | gender CHAR(1) â†’ 'M'      |
| TEXT       | Large text           | Description, blog content |


3ï¸.Date & Time Types


| Type      | Use                                    | Example               |
| --------- | -------------------------------------- | --------------------- |
| DATE      | yyyy-mm-dd                             | `2025-01-01`          |
| TIME      | hh:mm:ss                               | `10:45:20`            |
| DATETIME  | Full date + time                       | `2025-01-01 10:45:20` |
| TIMESTAMP | Auto system time (mostly used for log) |                       |



4ï¸.Boolean Type

| Type                 | Meaning              |
| -------------------- | -------------------- |
| BOOLEAN / TINYINT(1) | True or False values |


5ï¸.Other Special Types


| Type | Use                                            |
| ---- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| BLOB | Images, files                                  |
| ENUM | Predefined values only (e.g., gender: 'M','F') |



ğŸ§  Simple rule to remember


| Data Type | Use     |
| --------- | ------- |
| INT       | Numbers |
| VARCHAR   | Text    |
| DATE      | Date    |



â— Pro Tip

Phone number â†’ INT use panna koodathu âŒ
(reason: +91, 0 starting lost aagum)
Use â†’ VARCHAR(15) âœ”ï¸



Example - Better sladevelopers Table


CREATE TABLE sladevelopers(
  id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  name VARCHAR(50),
  age INT,
  salary DECIMAL(10,2),
  join_date DATE
);





7.=> what are all the constains in sql ?


Data correct-ah, secure-ah store panna constraints use pannuvom.

One English sentence:
â€œConstraints are rules applied to table columns to control valid data.â€


âœ”ï¸ SQL Constraints List

| Constraint         | Use                    | Tamil Meaning        | Example        |
| ------------------ | ---------------------- | -------------------- | -------------- |
| **PRIMARY KEY**    | Unique + Not Null      | Unmai unique ID      | id             |
| **FOREIGN KEY**    | Link tables            | Table connect pannum | dept_id        |
| **NOT NULL**       | Empty aagatha          | Value must give      | name           |
| **UNIQUE**         | Duplicate allowed illa | Orru value only      | email          |
| **CHECK**          | Condition enforce      | Rule fix             | age > 18       |
| **DEFAULT**        | No value kudukka       | Auto value set       | default status |
| **AUTO_INCREMENT** | Auto number increase   | ID auto generate     | 1,2,3â€¦         |



ğŸ§  Easy Summary

ğŸ”¹ PRIMARY KEY = unique + not null
ğŸ”¹ FOREIGN KEY = relationship between tables
ğŸ”¹ NOT NULL = must enter value
ğŸ”¹ UNIQUE = duplicate not allowed
ğŸ”¹ CHECK = rule to validate data
ğŸ”¹ DEFAULT = value auto fill
ğŸ”¹ AUTO_INCREMENT = numbering automatically



ğŸ”¥ Example Table with Constraints

CREATE TABLE employee (
  emp_id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,
  emp_name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
  email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE,
  age INT CHECK(age > 18),
  status VARCHAR(10) DEFAULT 'Active'
);



ğŸ¯ Quick Tip for Memory

P F N U C D A
Primary
Foreign
Not Null
Unique
Check
Default
Auto Increment





8.=>âœ”ï¸ Why ID and Primary Key are MUST in IT Companies?


1. IDENTIFICATION (Unique user identify panna)

*Per-la duplicate irukkum

*Per change aagalam (marriage, typo, etc.)

*Aana ID change aagakoodathu

So primary key = System identification
Example: user_id, emp_id

2ï¸.User Name does NOT guarantee uniqueness âŒ

Example:

*2 per â€œGowthamâ€

*10 per â€œKumarâ€

*â€œS. Kumarâ€, â€œKumar Sâ€ â†’ same person confused

So Name column UNIQUE aagakoodathu illa

ID â†’ UNIQUE âœ”ï¸

3ï¸.AUTO_INCREMENT use pannara reason

Example:


| Data Insert        | ID                   |
| ------------------ | -------------------- |
| 6th record added   | 6                    |
| 6th record deleted | (6 removed)          |
| New record insert  | **7** (not 6)** âœ”ï¸** |


ğŸ“Œ Because:

Database history & structure never gets confused
ID â†’ Oru naal generate pannina number repeat aagakoodathu

Even if row deleted â€” ID never reused
This is correct behavior ğŸ‘Œ

4ï¸.USER_VIEW vs SYSTEM_VIEW (Super Important ğŸ¯)



| View        | What user sees                  | What system stores       |
| ----------- | ------------------------------- | ------------------------ |
| User view   | Sl.No (1,2,3,4â€¦)                | Can be missing if delete |
| System view | Primary Key (like 68, 69, 1001) | Never reused             |



ğŸ§  Example:
User sees:

| No | Name    |
| -- | ------- |
| 1  | Ram     |
| 2  | Raj     |
| 3  | Krishna |


But system internally:


| user_id | name    |
| ------- | ------- |
| 68      | Ram     |
| 69      | Raj     |
| 75      | Krishna |



ğŸ‘‰ User never sees internal ID
ğŸ‘‰ Developer & database use internal ID for reference

5ï¸.WHY Internal ID gaps are OK?

âŒ Wrong thinking:

6 delete pannina â†’ Sl.No gap so waste

âœ” Correct thinking:

Gap irundhaalum safety + history preserve aagum
ID reused pannalainna
â†’ Confusion illa
â†’ Data corruption avoid

ğŸ“Œ Final Simple Summary (Notebook-ku ready)



| Rule                                | Reason                     |
| ----------------------------------- | -------------------------- |
| Every table must have a Primary Key | Unique identification      |
| Auto increment for ID               | Never repeat IDs           |
| Users should not see internal ID    | Security + clean UI        |
| Deletion gap acceptable             | Data safety & traceability |



Real Company Example



CREATE TABLE users(
  user_id INT PRIMARY KEY AUTO_INCREMENT,  -- System ID
  display_no INT,                          -- Optional UI number
  name VARCHAR(50) NOT NULL,
  email VARCHAR(50) UNIQUE
);





